    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>The Houck, Kibler, and Smith families are long term residents of Michigan, settling in Lenawee and Monroe Counties between the late 1840s and early 1900s. Their ancestors settled from Ohio, Pennsylvania, New York, England, Germany, and Switzerland. Isaac Harvey Houck and Lydia Ella Lang were Michigan farmers who married in 1885. They gave birth to six children: Lolla Mae, William Jacob, Harvey Roy, Anna Ellen, Cecile Mae, and Ellen. Anna Ellen Houck later married Ralph Enos Smith in 1922. Ralph Smith was also a farmer while Anna was a school teacher. Ralph and Anna had two children: Mae Gene, a school teacher, and Lowell, a World War II Air Force veteran and business owner. In 1945, Mae Gene married Melvin D. Kibler, a World War II Army veteran, farmer, and electrician. Melvin Kibler was the son of George and Sadie Blanche Kibler, who are also represented in this collection.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351">
      <p>This collection is organized by family unit and contains four series: Houck Family, Kibler Family, Smith Family, and Scrapbooks.</p>
    </arrangement>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>This genealogical collection traces the roots of three Michigan families. The papers include correspondence, estate records, visual materials, and war records.</p>
    </scopecontent>
